04330nam a22006375i 9780674033795DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212010mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740337957 a10.4159/97806740337952doi  a(DE-B1597)574434  a(OCoLC)1248760092  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQL737.P96 -- B39 2008eb 7aNAT0370002bisacsh04a599.88/15131 aBearzi, Maddalena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeautiful Minds :bThe Parallel Lives of Great Apes and Dolphins /cCraig B Stanford, Maddalena Bearzi. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Beautiful Minds -- t1 An Eternal Fascination -- t2 Two Histories Afield -- t3 Swimming with Dolphins, Swinging with Apes -- t4 Dolphin and Ape Societies—Whys and Wherefores -- t5 Cognition: Minds in the Sea and Forest -- t6 Master Politicians -- t7 Culture Vultures -- t8 Toward the Roots of Human Intelligence -- tConclusion: Beautiful Minds Are a Terrible Thing to Waste -- tFurther Reading -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aApes and dolphins: primates and cetaceans. Could any creatures appear to be more different? Yet both are large-brained intelligent mammals with complex communication and social interaction. In the first book to study apes and dolphins side by side, Maddalena Bearzi and Craig B. Stanford, a dolphin biologist and a primatologist who have spent their careers studying these animals in the wild, combine their insights with compelling results. Beautiful Minds explains how and why apes and dolphins are so distantly related yet so cognitively alike and what this teaches us about another large-brained mammal: Homo sapiens. Noting that apes and dolphins have had no common ancestor in nearly 100 million years, Bearzi and Stanford describe the parallel evolution that gave rise to their intelligence. And they closely observe that intelligence in action, in the territorial grassland and rainforest communities of chimpanzees and other apes, and in groups of dolphins moving freely through open coastal waters. The authors detail their subjects’ ability to develop family bonds, form alliances, and care for their young. They offer an understanding of their culture, politics, social structure, personality, and capacity for emotion. The resulting dual portrait—with striking overlaps in behavior—is key to understanding the nature of “beautiful minds.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aNATURE / Animals / Wildlife.2bisacsh1 aStanford, Craig B, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674033795423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674033795.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK